title: For Sale:  Benelli M4 9-round capacity 922(r) COMPLIANT!!!
postcontent: This Benelli M4 semi-automatic shotgun has been modified with a Carrier Comp titanium magazine tube, Carrier Comp hammer, and Brownell's magazine follower so that it has enough US made parts to be considered of US manufacture. Because of that, it is no longer subject to ATF code 922(r) which limits imported semi-auto shotguns with a pistol grip stock to 5 round magazines. Any Benelli with the extended magazine, which doesn't have enough additional US made parts is a felony to own. This weapon is 100% LEGAL! Included in the sale are all receipts proving US origin of parts, the original magazine tube, follower, and hammer, the original box, a Cabela's soft case, and all manufacturer's documentation. This is a gorgeous firearm, cycles flawlessly, is easy on the shoulder, and can put a 1oz slug through a bullseye at 50 yards off of the ghost rings. It's had approximately 100 rounds fired through it. I am selling it as I'm soon moving to a state with less accepting gun laws. My loss is your gain!

title: For Sale:  Springfield M1903 A3 rifle
location: Frederick, 25 miles north of Denver, Denver, Colorado
postcontent:
A sublime war relic, this Springfield 1903 A3 is an authentic piece of U.S. history and a durned good shooter, too. I have put a hundred-fifty rounds through it (I suggest you use a rubber stock cushion as your body won't like this treatment much) and it shoots nice 3 MOA groups through tired old eyes. Bore is close to being mirror-bright but does show a little frost near the chamber.

This rifle functions perfectly. The extractor is so strong it will pitch a spent case 20 feet! Feed and cutoff are perfect, all the finish is strongly phosphated green save a black bolt, and the rebuild was done in 1944 at the Ogden arsenal.

It's an amazing piece that you would be proud to add to your collection. Offered for $550, cash only, no trades.

postcontent:
I have a truly unique rifle offered for sale here; I had it custom made.

It is a K98k, dou marked, a Russian capture gun. I had it re-stocked with a military profile walnut stock, and a Leupold scope mount tapped into the top of the chamber. The entire rifle was configured with new parts from Numerich, it was bead-blasted and blued (the finish is unique and beautiful), and I had the rifle chambered in 6 mm Remington, because I wanted a fast, flat-shooting cartridge. It's had an action block installed in the magazine to prevent the short-action cartridges from moving forward under recoil, and the action has been slicked up to function with the new caliber as well. It's got a Timmney trigger and Bueller-style safety which clears the scope bell nicely - speaking of that, I've mounted a nice Nikon Monarch 3-12x40 scope with a side parallax adjustment as a telescopic sight.

With my handloads the rifle shoots moderately well, (1.5 MOA) but it's no mega-tack driver (although with the right reloader behind the press, it could show it's true capabilities). If you're buying it for that purpose, you can get a rifle these days for $400 that will bench under a minute. This rifle oozes CHARACTER, and attracts huge attention on the line during a competition shoot.

Offered for $800 with dies, brass for about 100 rounds,, some loads ready to shoot, and nearly 800 Hornady 105-grain bullets.

title: For Sale/Trade:  45 bullets, bullseye and unique powder
postcontent:
Helping out fellow reloaders as I recently bought a decent quantity of lead and am willing to sell bullets(bullets, not loaded rounds... half ounce chunks of lead...). Im going off of what one would pay to by 230 grain 45 from the cheapest source (missouri bullet co- $45/500+14 s&h. I'll sell mine for $55/500 and you dont have to wait the extra 4 to 5 weeks to get back to loading! 230gr truncated cone bullets. Actual weight is ~232gr due to alloy. These are casted from 100% clip on wheel weights(harder) and have a hardness of about 12bhn. If you want harder bullets for higher velocities, I can quench them at a hardness about 18bhn for an extra $5/500 lot. Truncated cone bullets make a nice clean hole in a paper target like a wad cutter, but they feed like a round nose. I have shot these through multiple 1911's, glocks, sigs etc etc. As long as they are loaded  correctly, they are a excellent bullet. $55/500 bullets

I also have a pound of both alliant bullseye and alliant unique powder for sale. bullseye is trusted powder for 38 and 45 target loads but works for many other calibers as well. Unique is good from the anemic 25acp to moderate 44 magnum loads. $35 each or 60 if you buy both

title: For Sale/Trade:  Ruger "New Model" Super Blackhawk .44 Magnum
postcontent:
I'm selling my lightly customized .44 Magnum Ruger Super Blackhawk. It is a modified New Model type with a seven and a half inch barrel. It is well used but never mistreated, with some small nicks and bare spots toward the muzzle, a narrow band of tiny pitting spots in a line on one small section of the cylinder, and some carry wear and finish loss on the handle backstrap. Where the blue remains, however, it remains quite deep and can be quite striking in the right light.

This weapon has been lightly--and, if need be, reversibly--customized, with a Power Custom hammer that both tightened and slicked up the action considerably and also added an extra notch so that, like the "old model" Blackhawks, it can be set to half-cock. This allows the the chambers to index neatly with the loading gate when reloading. Current owners of unmodified New Model Blackhawks will understand the difference, and the awkwardness of having to hold the cylinder just so rather than it simply clicking into the right spot. It also adds a delightful extra "click" to the cocking action. Essentially you get all the advantages of both the old and new model Ruger actions: the hammer bar safety allowing it to be safely carried with all six chambers loaded, and the extra cocking notch for proper indexing and that classic "feel."

A well used gun, but a very fun one to shoot with an action that feels better and tighter than a factory new one. I've upgraded to a Freedom Arms model for my big-bore single-action needs and don't really need this Ruger anymore, but I don't particularly need to get rid of it either.  The listed price is how much money I have in the gun plus the custom parts, but I'm well aware that the nature of custom guns is you can't reasonably expect to get back the same amount back out. Make whatever offer you would consider fair, and I will consider it.

Also note that it comes with all of the original parts, which can be easily reinstalled without alteration, as well as a number of extras. Several Wolff mainsprings of varying weights. A Power Custom alternative pawl that would allow the cylinder to spin in both directions when the gun is NOT set to half-cock, but was never installed as it requires minor gunsmithing to fit that I never got around to. The gun is pictured wearing Hogue Micarta grips (I find the extra thickness to take the sharpness out of the recoil), but it will also come with its well worn walnut originals. I'll even throw in its old leather Western style holster, which is nothing special but quite functional.
